==Fundamental applications==
Historically, matrix multiplication has been introduced for facilitating and clarifying computations in linear algebra. This strong relationship between matrix multiplication and linear algebra remains fundamental in all mathematics, as well as in physics, chemistry, engineering and computer science.

===Linear maps===
If a vector space has a finite basis, its vectors are each uniquely represented by a finite sequence of scalars, called a coordinate vector, whose elements are the coordinates of the vector on the basis. These coordinate vectors form another vector space, which is isomorphic to the original vector space. A coordinate vector is commonly organized as a column matrix (also called a &quot;column vector&quot;), which is a matrix with only one column. So, a column vector represents both a coordinate vector, and a vector of the original vector space.

A linear map from a vector space of dimension into a vector space of dimension maps a column vector
:formula_35
onto the column vector
:formula_36
The linear map is thus defined by the matrix 
:formula_37
and maps the column vector formula_5 to the matrix product 
:formula_39

If is another linear map from the preceding vector space of dimension , into a vector space of dimension , it is represented by a matrix formula_40 A straightforward computation shows that the matrix of the composite map is the matrix product formula_41 The general formula ) that defines the function composition is instanced here as a specific case of associativity of matrix product (see below):
:formula_42

====Geometric rotations====

Using a Cartesian coordinate system in a Euclidean plane, the rotation by an angle formula_43 around the origin is a linear map.
More precisely, 
formula_44
where the source point formula_45 and its image formula_46 are written as column vectors.

The composition of the rotation by formula_43 and that by formula_48 then corresponds to the matrix product
formula_49
where appropriate trigonometric identities are employed for the second equality.
That is, the composition corresponds to the rotation by angle formula_50, as expected.

====Resource allocation in economics====

As an example, a fictitious factory uses 4 kinds of basic commodities, formula_51 to produce 3 kinds of intermediate goods, formula_52, which in turn are used to produce 3 kinds of final products, formula_53. The matrices 
:formula_54   and   formula_55
provide the amount of basic commodities needed for a given amount of intermediate goods, and the amount of intermediate goods needed for a given amount of final products, respectively.
For example, to produce one unit of intermediate good formula_56, one unit of basic commodity formula_57, two units of formula_58, no units of formula_59, and one unit of formula_60 are needed, corresponding to the first column of formula_61.

Using matrix multiplication, compute 
:formula_62
this matrix directly provides the amounts of basic commodities needed for given amounts of final goods. For example, the bottom left entry of formula_63 is computed as formula_64, reflecting that formula_65 units of formula_60 are needed to produce one unit of formula_67. Indeed, one formula_60 unit is needed for formula_56, one for each of two formula_70, and formula_71 for each of the four formula_72 units that go into the formula_67 unit, see picture.

In order to produce e.g. 100 units of the final product formula_67, 80 units of formula_75, and 60 units of formula_76, the necessary amounts of basic goods can be computed as
